[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/10th-tennessee-infantry-regiment-union] The **10th Tennessee Infantry Regiment** was an infantry regiment that served in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/10th-tennessee-infantry-regiment-union] Originally recruited and designated as the **1st Middle Tennessee Infantry**, it was largely composed of Irish-Americans.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/10th-tennessee-infantry-regiment-union] The 10th Tennessee Infantry was organized at Nashville, Tennessee, from May until August 1862, and mustered in for a three-year enlistment under the command of Colonel Alvan Cullem Gillem.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] The **1853 Tennessee gubernatorial election** was held on August 4, 1853, to elect the Governor of Tennessee.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Democratic nominee and former member of the U.S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] House of Representatives from Tennessee's 1st district Andrew Johnson defeated Whig nominee Gustavus Adolphus Henry Sr.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 4, 1853, Democratic nominee Andrew Johnson won the election by a margin of 2,252 votes against his Whig opponent Gustavus Adolphus Henry Sr., thereby gaining Democratic control over the office of Governor.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1853-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Johnson was sworn in as the 15th Governor of Tennessee on October 17, 1853.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] The **1855 Tennessee gubernatorial election** was held on August 2, 1855, to elect the governor of Tennessee.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic governor Andrew Johnson was re-elected against Whig nominee and former member of the U.S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] House of Representatives from Tennessee's 7th district Meredith Poindexter Gentry.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] On election day, August 2, 1855, incumbent Democratic governor Andrew Johnson won re-election by a margin of 2,157 votes against his Whig opponent Meredith Poindexter Gentry, thereby retaining Democratic control over the office of governor.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1855-tennessee-gubernatorial-election] Johnson was sworn in for his second term on October 17, 1855.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The **1860 Democratic National Conventions** were a series of presidential nominating conventions held to nominate the Democratic Party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1860 election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The first convention, held from April 23 to May 3 in Charleston, South Carolina, deadlocked after failing to nominate a ticket: two subsequent conventions, both held in Baltimore, Maryland in June, ultimately nominated separate presidential tickets.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Opponents of Douglas's nomination spread their support among five major candidates, including former Treasury Secretary James Guthrie of Kentucky and Senator Robert M.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After 57 ballots over a span of two days, in which Douglas consistently won at least half of the delegates, the Charleston convention adjourned when it became apparent no candidate could secure the required two-thirds of all votes.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The Democratic convention reconvened in Baltimore on June 18, but many Southern delegates were either excluded from the convention or refused to participate.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The convention adopted a platform in which it pledged to abide by the decision of the Supreme Court of the United States upon questions of Constitutional Law regarding slavery.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Douglas was ultimately nominated for president on the second ballot (the 59th ballot overall).
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Senator Benjamin Fitzpatrick of Alabama was nominated for vice president, but he refused the nomination, and was replaced by former Governor Herschel V.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The Southern Democrats who had boycotted, or walked out of, the Baltimore convention held their own separate convention and adopted a pro-slavery platform, and nominated incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Breckinridge for president, with Senator Joseph Lane of Oregon as vice president.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] While Douglas and Breckinridge received a combined 47.62% of the popular vote in the 1860 presidential election, they lost the election to Republican candidate Abraham Lincoln.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The front-runner for the nomination was Douglas, who was considered a moderate on the slavery issue.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] However, the Supreme Court’s ensuing 1857 'Dred Scott' decision declared that the Constitution protected slavery in all Territories.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Many of them openly predicted a split in the party and the election of Republican front-runner William H.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The 1860 Democratic National Convention convened at South Carolina Institute Hall (destroyed in the Great Fire of 1861) in Charleston, South Carolina, on April 23, 1860: the galleries at the convention were packed with pro-slavery spectators.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Urged by Yancey, the delegations from seven Deep South states (Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Texas) met in a separate caucus before the convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] They reached a tentative consensus to "stop Douglas" by imposing a pro-slavery party platform which he could not run on if nominated.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The "Fire-eater" majority on the convention's platform committee, chaired by William Waightstill Avery of North Carolina, produced an explicitly pro-slavery document, endorsing *Dred Scott* and Congressional legislation protecting slavery in the territories.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Douglas and supporters thus preferred the 1856 Cincinnati platform.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] On April 30, the minority (Northern) report was substituted for that of the majority (Southern) report by a vote of 165 to 138.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The question next in order before the convention was upon the adoption of the second resolution of the minority of the committee: on this question Alabama, Arkansas, one of Delaware's delegates, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Texas refused to vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The Douglas party abandoned the vague second resolution, and it was defeated by an overwhelming vote of 238 to 21 (with 44 abstentions).
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Between April 30 and May 1, 51 Southern delegates walked out of the convention in protest: the entire delegations of Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, South Carolina and Texas, three of the four delegates from Arkansas and one of the three delegates from Delaware.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Andrews Hall on Broad Street and declared themselves the real convention as the Institute Hall convention proceeded to nominations.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Since both the majority and the minority resolutions on the Territorial question were rejected, nothing remained except the Cincinnati platform as the Douglas faction had desired.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The dominant Douglas forces believed their path was now clear.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Before the balloting for president commenced, Mr.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] It was well known at the time that this resolution would render the regular nomination of Douglas impossible.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Six major candidates were nominated at the convention: Douglas, former Treasury Secretary James Guthrie of Kentucky, Senator Robert M.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Hunter of Virginia, Senator Joseph Lane of Oregon, former Senator Daniel S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Dickinson of New York, and Senator Andrew Johnson of Tennessee.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] This ruling meant Douglas needed 202 votes (56+1⁄2 more votes), or 80% of the remaining 253 delegates: this was all but impossible as it would have required several of the remaining Southern delegates to vote for Douglas, who they vehemently opposed.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Consequently, the convention held 57 ballots, and though Douglas led on all of them, he never received more than 152+1⁄2 votes.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] On the 57th ballot, Douglas received 151+1⁄2 votes, still 50+1⁄2 votes short of the nomination, though far ahead of Guthrie, who was second with 65+1⁄2.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] On 3 May, the delegates voted to adjourn the convention, and reconvene in Baltimore six weeks later.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] A few votes went to former Senator Isaac Toucey of Connecticut and Senator James Pearce of Maryland, while Senator Jefferson Davis of Mississippi (the future Confederate President) received one vote on over fifty ballots from Benjamin Butler of Massachusetts.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Ironically, during the Civil War, Butler became a Union general, and Davis ordered him hanged as a criminal if he was captured.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The Democrats re-convened at the Front Street Theater (destroyed in the Great Baltimore Fire of 1904) in Baltimore, Maryland, on 18 June.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The southern walk-out delegates had reconvened at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond where it was decided by many delegates to attend the Baltimore convention before giving up on their fellow Democrats.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] However, the South Carolina delegation chose to remain in Richmond.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The resumed convention's first business was to decide whether to re-admit the delegates who had walked out of the Charleston session, or to seat replacement delegates who had been named by pro-Douglas Democrats in some states: other delegates had boycotted the Baltimore convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The credentials committee's majority report recommended re-admitting all delegates except those from Louisiana and Alabama, while the minority report recommended re-admitting some of the Louisiana and Alabama delegates as well.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] On June 22, the minority (Southern) report failed to be substituted for that of the majority (Northern) report by a vote of 100+1⁄2-150.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the rejection of the minority report, two votes were taken on the reconsideration of the substitution vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] At first, New York revived hopes of adopting the minority report by voting for its reconsideration.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] But during the second vote on reconsideration, New York switched back to its original vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] With the admission of the new Louisiana and Alabama delegates, 56 delegates - most of those remaining from the South, and a scattering of delegates from northern and far western states - all walked out of the convention in protest.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the convention resumed voting on a nominee, Douglas received 173+1⁄2 of the 190+1⁄2 votes cast on the first ballot (the 58th overall), and 181+1⁄2 votes of the 194+1⁄2 votes cast on the second ballot (the 59th overall).
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] A rollcall was taken following the second ballot, and it was realized that there were only 194+1⁄2 delegates present, meaning that there were insufficient delegates for Douglas to receive the 202 votes required by Cushing's ruling at the first convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the delegates unanimously voted to rescind that ruling, it was declared by acclamation that Douglas had received the required two-thirds of the votes cast, and he was therefore nominated.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Senator Benjamin Fitzpatrick of Alabama was the only candidate for the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] During the call of the states, every vote recorded was in favor of Fitzpatrick with no exception until Pennsylvania was reached.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] One of Pennsylvania's votes was announced for former state senator William C.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Upon this announcement, a New Jersey delegate informed the delegates that he had been authorized before the convention, by Alexander himself, not to allow his name to be presented as a candidate.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The Pennsylvanian who desired Alexander cast one blank vote thereafter.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the unanimous nomination of Fitzpatrick as the candidate for vice president, the convention adjourned on June 23, the sixth and last day of its session.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] On the same day, but after the adjournment, Fitzpatrick declined the nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Fitzpatrick's refusal of the vice-presidential nomination occurred sixteen years after Silas Wright was the first to turndown the honor.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] In 1924, Frank Lowden would be the third and last person to date who refused their party's vice-presidential nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Since the convention had already adjourned, the executive committee was required to name a replacement for Fitzpatrick.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Dick, the lone remaining delegate from North Carolina, the vice-presidential nomination was conferred on former Senator and Governor Herschel V.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] A second convention assembled at Instituted Hall in Baltimore on June 23, 1860.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] It was composed chiefly of the delegates who had walked out of or boycotted the Northern Democratic convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] One of their first acts was to abrogate the two-thirds rule, as had been done by the Douglas convention: both conventions acted under the same necessity, since there were insufficient delegates remaining to allow the preservation of this rule at either convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The majority resolutions, whose replacement by the minority report facilitated the collapse of the Charleston convention, were reported and adopted unanimously, amid great applause.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the adoption of the majority resolutions, the convention proceeded to select their candidates.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Four names were placed in nomination: Breckinridge, Dickinson, Hunter, and Lane.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Despite instructions from their state convention, the Mississippi delegation, with Jefferson Davis' concurrence, desired that his name be removed from possible consideration for the sake of harmony.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The names of Hunter and Lane were subsequently withdrawn in the spirit of harmony and unanimity.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After New York cast an obligatory vote for Dickinson, Breckinridge was declared the unanimous choice of the convention for president.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the applause for Breckinridge's nomination had subsided, the whole hall resounded with cries for Yancey for Vice President.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After Yancey got on his feet, but before he could speak, Lane's name was presented and seconded.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] No other names being presented for the office, the states were called and voted unanimously for Lane.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After this, many delegates returned to Metropolitan Hall in Richmond so that those who had remained there could also vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] On June 26, the delegates present voted for Breckenridge and Lane, concurring with the convention at the Maryland Institute Hall.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] After the break-up of the Charleston convention, many of those present stated that the Republicans were now certain to win the 1860 Presidential election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] In the general election, the actual division in Democratic popular votes did not directly affect any state outcomes except California, Oregon, Kentucky, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Of these states, only California and Oregon were free states, and although both were carried by Republican nominee Abraham Lincoln they combined for only seven of Lincoln's 180 electoral votes.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] The latter three states were slave states that were carried by neither Douglas, Breckinridge nor Lincoln but by John Bell, nominee of the Constitutional Union Party.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Composed mainly of former Whigs and Know-Nothings, the Constitutional Union Party attempted to ignore the slavery issue in favor of preserving the Union.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Even if California, Oregon and every state carried by Douglas, Breckinridge or Bell had been carried by a single presidential nominee, Lincoln would still have had a large majority of electoral votes.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] However, the split in the Democratic Party organization was a serious handicap in many states, especially Pennsylvania, and almost certainly reduced the aggregate Democratic popular vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Pennsylvania's 27 electoral votes were especially decisive in ensuring a Republican victory – had Lincoln failed to carry that state combined with any other free state, he could not have obtained a majority of electoral votes, forcing a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] McPherson suggested in *Battle Cry of Freedom* that the “Fire-eater” program of breaking up the convention and running a rival ticket was deliberately intended to bring about the election of a Republican as president, and thus trigger secession declarations by the slave-owning states.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1860-democratic-national-conventions] Whatever the “intent” of the fire-eaters may have been, doubtless many of them favored secession, and the logical, probable, and actual consequence of their actions was to fragment the Democratic party and thereby virtually ensure a Republican victory.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The **1864 National Union National Convention** was the United States presidential nominating convention of the National Union Party, which met in Baltimore, Maryland on June 7 and 8, 1864.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] National Union was the name adopted by the main faction of the Republican Party in a coalition with many, if not most, War Democrats and Unconditional Unionists after some Republicans and War Democrats nominated John C.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont over Lincoln a few weeks earlier.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Union renominated Abraham Lincoln for president and Andrew Johnson was nominated for vice president.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] During the convention, the party adopted a platform calling for a victorious end in the ongoing Civil War, the eradication of slavery by constitutional amendment and the enforcement of the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party name was created in May 1864, during the Civil War, ahead of the 1864 presidential election, in which President Abraham Lincoln, then a Republican, was running for reelection.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont, who had been the Republicans' first presidential nominee during the 1856 election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] It was hoped that this act would cause someone other than Lincoln to gain the Republican nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] Republicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party at the convention in Baltimore, Maryland, during the first week in June 1864, in order to accommodate the War Democrats who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the Copperheads.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention dropped then-Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, a Radical Republican from the ticket, and chose War Democrat Andrew Johnson as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Unionists hoped that the new party and the Lincoln–Johnson ticket would stress the national character of the war.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party supported a Platform of 11 resolutions.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] Dennis Francis Murphy, member of the Official Corps of Reporters for the U.S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] On the first ballot, Missouri delegates cast their 22 votes for General Ulysses S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The Missourians quickly changed their votes to make Lincoln's renomination unanimous.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] Though Hamlin was willing to serve another term as vice president, he privately made it known that he was willing to step aside if a candidate who would be a greater electoral asset to Lincoln could be found.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention therefore nominated Andrew Johnson, the military governor of Tennessee.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] Lincoln had refused to weigh in on his preferred running mate, and the convention chose to nominate Johnson, a Southern War Democrat, in order to boost the party's appeal to Unionists of both parties.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-national-union-national-convention] In keeping with the tradition of the time, Lincoln did not attend the convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1864, near the end of the American Civil War.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President Abraham Lincoln of the National Union Party easily defeated the Democratic nominee, former General George B.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, by a wide margin of 212–21 in the electoral college, with 55% of the popular vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For the election, the Republican Party and some Democrats created the National Union Party, especially to attract War Democrats.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite some intra-party opposition from Salmon Chase and the Radical Republicans, Lincoln won his party's nomination at the 1864 National Union National Convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than re-nominate Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, the convention selected Andrew Johnson of Tennessee, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were divided between the Copperheads, who favored immediate peace with the Confederacy, and War Democrats, who supported the war.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 Democratic National Convention nominated McClellan, a War Democrat, but adopted a platform advocating peace with the Confederacy, which McClellan rejected, although his running mate George H.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] While the Confederacy seemed to have survival potential in summer 1864, it was visibly collapsing by election day in November.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his early fears of defeat, Lincoln won strong majorities in the popular and electoral vote, partly as a result of the recent Union victory at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War was still raging, no electoral votes were counted from any of the eleven southern states that had joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's re-election ensured that he would preside over the successful conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's victory made him the first president to win re-election since Andrew Jackson in 1832, as well as the first Northern president to ever win re-election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was assassinated six weeks into his second term.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was succeeded by his vice president, Andrew Johnson, who favored quick restoration of the seceded states to the Union without protection for the former slaves.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This led to conflict with the Republican-dominated Congress, culminating in Johnson's impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1868; he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election took place during the American Civil War.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] According to the Miller Center for the study of the presidency, the election was noteworthy for occurring at all, an unprecedented democratic exercise in the midst of a civil war.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Republican dissidents who called themselves Radical Republicans formed a party named the Radical Democratic Party and nominated John C.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont as their candidate for president.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont later withdrew and endorsed Lincoln.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] War Democrats joined with Republicans as the National Union Party, with Lincoln at the head of the ticket.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The National Union Party was a temporary name used to attract War Democrats and Southern Border State Unionists who would not vote for the Republican Party.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It faced off against the regular Democratic Party, including Peace Democrats.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election conventions of the parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War progressed, political opinions within the Republican Party began to diverge.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Senators Charles Sumner and Henry Wilson from Massachusetts wanted the Republican Party to advocate constitutional amendments to prohibit slavery and guarantee racial equality before the law.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, not all northern Republicans supported such measures.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders hoped that the radical Republicans would put forth their own ticket in the election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* newspaper, particularly interested in undermining the National Union Party, ran a series of articles predicting a delay for the National Union Convention until late in 1864 to allow Frémont time to collect delegates to win the nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont supporters in New York City established a newspaper called the *New Nation*, which declared in one of its initial issues that the National Union Convention would be a "nonentity".
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* also published false information (further purported by Samuel S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Before the election, some War Democrats joined the Republicans to form the National Union Party.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With the outcome of the Civil War still in doubt, some political leaders, including Salmon P.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase, Benjamin Wade, and Horace Greeley, opposed Lincoln's re-nomination on the grounds that he could not win.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase himself became the only candidate to contest Lincoln's re-nomination actively, but he withdrew in March when a slew of Republican officials, including some within the state of Ohio upon whom Chase's campaign depended, endorsed Lincoln for re-nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was still popular with most members of the Republican Party, and the National Union Party nominated him for a second term as president at their convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on June 7–8, 1864.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent vice president Hannibal Hamlin remaining indifferent about the prospect of a second term in office, Andrew Johnson, the former senator from and current military governor of Tennessee, was named as Lincoln's vice presidential running-mate.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He had been governor of Tennessee from 1853 to 1857 and was elected by the legislature to the Senate in 1857.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat in 1862.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern slave states, including Tennessee, seceded, he remained firmly with the Union.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was the only sitting senator from a Confederate state who did not resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as military governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1864, Johnson was a logical choice as running mate for Lincoln, who wished to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign, especially to ensure the electoral votes of the border states.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Others who were considered for the nomination, at one point or another, were former Senator Daniel Dickinson, Major General Benjamin Butler, Major General William Rosecrans, Joseph Holt, and former Treasury Secretary and Senator John Dix.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was bitterly split between War Democrats and Peace Democrats, a group further divided among competing factions.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Moderate Peace Democrats who supported the war against the Confederacy, such as Horatio Seymour, were preaching the wisdom of a negotiated peace.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After the Union victory at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, moderate Peace Democrats proposed a negotiated peace that would secure Union victory.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They believed this was the best course of action, because an armistice could finish the war without devastating the South.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Radical Peace Democrats known as Copperheads, such as Thomas H.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Seymour, declared the war to be a failure and favored an immediate end to hostilities without securing Union victory.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan vied for the presidential nomination.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, friends of Horatio Seymour insisted on placing his name before the convention, which was held in Chicago, Illinois, on August 29–31, 1864.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] But on the day before the organization of that body, Horatio Seymour announced positively that he would not be a candidate.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Since the Democrats were divided by issues of war and peace, they sought a strong candidate who could unify the party.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The compromise was to nominate pro-war General George B.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan for president and anti-war Representative George H.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, a War Democrat, was nominated for president over the Copperhead Thomas H.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Pendleton, a close associate of the Copperhead Clement Vallandigham, balanced the ticket, since he was known for having strongly opposed the Union war effort.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention adopted a peace platform – a platform McClellan personally rejected.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan supported the continuation of the war and restoration of the Union, but the party platform, written by Vallandigham, opposed this position.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Radical Democratic Convention assembled in Ohio with delegates arriving on May 29, 1864.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] *The New York Times* reported that the hall which the convention organizers had planned to use had been double-booked by an opera troupe.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Almost all delegates were instructed to support Frémont, with a major exception being the New York delegation, which was composed of War Democrats who supported Ulysses S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Various estimates of the number of delegates were reported in the press; *The New York Times* reported 156 delegates, but the number generally reported elsewhere was 350 delegates.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates came from 15 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They adopted the name Radical Democratic Party.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A supporter of Grant was appointed chairman.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The platform was passed with little discussion, and a series of resolutions that bogged down the convention proceedings were voted down decisively.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Frémont for president, and he accepted the nomination on June 4, 1864.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his letter, he stated that he would step aside if the National Union Convention would nominate someone other than Lincoln for president.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] John Cochrane was nominated for vice president.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 election was the first time since 1812 that a presidential election took place during a war.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For much of 1864, Lincoln himself believed he had little chance of being re-elected.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Confederate forces had triumphed at the Battle of Mansfield, the Battle of Cold Harbor, the Battle of Brices Cross Roads, the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain and the Battle of the Crater.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the war was continuing to take a very high toll in terms of casualties with campaigns such as Grant's Overland Campaign and the perceived lack of progress.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of a long and bloody war started to make the idea of "peace at all cost" offered by the Ultra Peace Democrats look more desirable.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] However, several political and military events eventually made Lincoln's re-election inevitable.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the first place, the Democrats had to confront the severe internal strains within their party at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The political compromises made at the Democratic National Convention were contradictory and made McClellan's efforts to campaign seem inconsistent.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Secondly, the Democratic National Convention influenced Frémont's campaign.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was appalled at the Democratic platform, which he described as "union with slavery".
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After three weeks of discussions with Cochrane and his supporters, Frémont withdrew from the race in September 1864.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his statement, Frémont declared that winning the Civil War was too important to divide the Republican vote.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Although he still felt that Lincoln was not going far enough, the defeat of McClellan was of the greatest necessity.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] General Cochrane, who was a War Democrat, agreed and withdrew with Frémont.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, 1864, Frémont also brokered a political deal in which Lincoln removed U.S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Montgomery Blair from office, and on September 24 Abraham Lincoln relieved Blair of his duty as Postmaster General.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan's chances of victory faded after Frémont withdrew from the presidential race.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lastly, with the fall of Atlanta on September 2, there was no longer any question that a Union military victory was inevitable and close at hand.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Union Party mobilized the full strength of both the Republicans and the War Democrats under the slogan "Don't change horses in the middle of a stream".
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It was energized as Lincoln made emancipation the central issue, and state Republican parties stressed the perfidy of the Copperheads.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] 24.4% of the voting age population and 76.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The American Civil War was in progress and unfinished during this election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Because eleven Southern states plus two claimed additional Southern states had declared secession from the Union and formed the Confederate States of America, only twenty-five states participated in the election.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Louisiana and Tennessee had recently been re-captured.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They chose presidential electors, but their votes were rejected by Congress due to having recently seceded from the Union.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Both states had voted for Lincoln, so it would not have changed the result in any case.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Three new states participated for the first time: Kansas, West Virginia, and Nevada.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan won just three states: Kentucky, Delaware, and his home state of New Jersey.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln won in every state he carried in 1860 except New Jersey, and also carried a state won four years earlier by Stephen Douglas (Missouri), one carried by John C.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge (Maryland) and all three newly admitted states (Kansas, Nevada and West Virginia).
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Altogether, 212 electoral votes were counted in Congress for Lincoln – more than enough to win the presidency even if all of the states in rebellion had participated and voted against him.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the last election in which a party nominee won completely different states than the previous nominee, with McClellan flipping Kentucky and New Jersey, while having lost Missouri.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was highly popular with soldiers and they in turn recommended him to their families back home.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The following states allowed soldiers to cast ballots: California, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Rhode Island, and Wisconsin.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Only soldiers from Kentucky gave McClellan a majority of their votes, and he carried the army vote in the state by a vote of 2,823 (70.3%) to 1,194 (29.7%).
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,129 counties making returns, Lincoln won in 728 (64.5%), while McClellan carried 400 (35.4%).
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.1%) in Iowa split evenly between Lincoln and McClellan.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election the Republicans won in Maryland until 1896.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The states in rebellion did not participate in the election of 1864.* (b) *The 17 electoral votes from Tennessee and Louisiana were rejected.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1864-united-states-presidential-election] States in red were won by Republican Abraham Lincoln; states in blue were won by Democrat George B.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1865-state-of-the-union-address] The **1865 State of the Union Address** was written by historian George Bancroft and read to the Congress by Robert Johnson, the son and personal secretary of the 17th president of the United States, Andrew Johnson.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1865-state-of-the-union-address] According to one historian, "Johnson had sent Bancroft only two suggestions: passages from Thomas Jefferson's inaugural and from a speech by Charles James Fox." The result was generally high-toned and well received.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1865-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented to the United States Congress on Monday, December 4, 1865.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/1865-state-of-the-union-address] The text stated, "Our thoughts next revert to the death of the late President by an act of parricidal treason.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles Johnson was remembered as his mother's favorite.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] She was said to have "never quite recovered" from her grief at his early death.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles Johnson's death is sometimes mentioned as one of the causes for Eliza Johnson's self-isolation during the family's White House years.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] He was noted for both his conviviality but also his "dissipation," and he is believed to have suffered from the same alcoholism that contributed to his brother Robert Johnson's death in 1869.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Born 1830 in the family's Main Street house in Greeneville, Tennessee, Charles Johnson was the second-born of Andrew Johnson's five children with Eliza McCardle.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles Johnson was working in Greeneville at age 20 as a printer at the time of the 1850 census.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] For about a year he was a partner in a newspaper called the *Greeneville Spy*, and circa 1857 he co-owned a drugstore and worked as a druggist.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles and his brother Robert also managed their father's business affairs and real estate when Andrew Johnson was away from Tennessee.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] At the time of the 1860 census, when he was 30, he was living in the family home, but his occupation was now listed as physician.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] But that same year, he also visited Charleston, South Carolina, for the 1860 Democratic National Convention and had "gotten on a spree" that had troubled the family, meaning that he had been drunk for the duration to the point that his brother had a hard time even getting him out of the city.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] In January 1861, as the nation was collapsing into civil war, Andrew Johnson's son Robert reported that Charles had gone on another "spree." Both Johnson brothers were delegates from Greene County at the May–June 1861 pro-Union East Tennessee Convention.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] When Tennessee went for the Confederacy, both Southern Unionist Johnson sons were wanted men, their brother-in-law David T.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Patterson was imprisoned, and their brother-in-law Daniel Stover, a leader of the East Tennessee bridge burners, would have been summarily executed by CSA troops had he been captured.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Andrew Johnson was made military governor of Tennessee by President Lincoln and the U.S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles apparently traveled with him to the capital in the fall of 1862, where he enlisted in the federal army.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] He served as an assistant surgeon under Rudolph Knaffl in the 10th Tennessee Infantry Regiment of the U.S.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Army, which was also known as the Middle Tennessee Infantry.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles Johnson died at Nashville during the American Civil War after being thrown from a horse.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] As one bio put it, his death was "under circumstances that were never quite clear." Two news accounts stated that he was killed almost instantly due to a traumatic head injury.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] An account published in 1891 stated, "Of the three bright, promising sons born to [Andrew Johnson] all died victims of the same enemy that carried the illustrious father away—the bottle.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] One of the young men was a dear fellow who I knew and loved well.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] One day during the war he was toppled from his horse on the streets of Nashville, Tenn.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] According to Paul Bergeron, a University of Tennessee historian and the last of three major editors of *The Papers of Andrew Johnson*, "Charles...had been cursed for many years with a serious drinking problem.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Many believed he was drunk on the day of his fatal accident." The family was notified by telegram from Tennessee Secretary of State Edward H.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] The only family member able to attend the April 7, 1863, funeral was Robert Johnson, and the funeral procession included part of his regiment, the 1st Tennessee Cavalry.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] National Park Service, which operates the Andrew Johnson National Historic Site, Charles Johnson was originally buried at Mount Olivet in the Tennessee state capital.
[src:charles-johnson-tennessee/charles-johnson-tennessee] Charles Johnson does not appear by name in the Mount Olivet burial record for April 1863, but there is a "Mrs.
